# Code Structure

This is the project's coding style. Favor readability and learnability above cleverness.

## Guiding patterns
- **Composed Method** (Kent Beck): every function is composed of calls to other
  well-named functions at the same level of abstraction. Read the top like a
  summary; "drill down" via Go to Definition (ctrl+click).
- **Functional Core, Imperative Shell** (Gary Bernhardt): pure logic in the
  core, side effects (UI, storage, network) only at the edges.
- No single `main` is required - composition is what matters, not a fixed entry
  point. Any function can be an entry; favor functions over functions.

## Backend - functional
- Function per function: small, single-purpose, descriptively named pure
  functions composed together (the functional core).
- Functions for behavior; typed objects for data shapes.
- Don't over-fragment: decompose where it aids understanding, not blindly.

## Frontend - technical & idiomatic
- Follow the chosen framework's idiomatic structure strictly (components /
  composables / state), strongly typed throughout. (Detailed once the stack is
  locked - DEFERRED.)
- The frontend is a thin shell that calls the backend's pure functions; keep
  business logic out of the UI.

## Organize folders by technical responsibility
- Group code into NARROW, purpose-named folders by what they do (e.g. `money/`,
  `validation/`, `calculation/`, `dates/`, `types/`).
- Never a broad catch-all `utils/`. Files in a folder must genuinely relate to
  that folder's single responsibility.

## Self-documenting folders + source of truth
- Each folder has an index/barrel file that re-exports its functions, with a
  one-line header comment describing the folder's job.
- Keep barrels shallow: one per folder; barrels do NOT import other barrels
  (avoids circular imports). Direct imports are fine when needed.
- One MAIN function per file, file named after that function (`formatPeso.ts` ->
  `formatPeso`). Small private helpers may share the file.
- Deep/technical explanations of folders, files, and trade-offs live in the
  **logic map** (`.context/architecture/logic-map.md`) - the single source of
  truth. Do not scatter per-folder README files.

## Favor reusable generics - but not prematurely
- Extract generic, dependency-free helpers so they can be reused (DRY).
- Apply the rule of three: abstract into a generic only after real repetition
  (~3 uses), not preemptively (avoid premature abstraction).

## Naming
- Names carry the readability. Keep function/file names precise and intention-
  revealing so the ctrl+click "drill down" workflow stays reliable.
